{"ts": "2026-06-08T23:50:24.543026+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 80725b99ed71ad1bd87e5c9cc824bfc95abe641e)", "id": "lc_f12aa392-a68b-4e61-93b3-5dcd34a3c29a"}, {"type": "text", "text": "package io.dodn.springboot.test.api;\n\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.BeforeEach;\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Tag;\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.extension.ExtendWith;\nimport org.springframework.restdocs.RestDocumentationContextProvider;\nimport org.springframework.restdocs.RestDocumentationExtension;\nimport org.springframework.restdocs.mockmvc.MockMvcRestDocumentation;\nimport org.springframework.test.web.servlet.MockMvc;\nimport org.springframework.test.web.servlet.setup.MockMvcBuilders;\n\n@Tag(\"restdocs\")\n@ExtendWith(RestDocumentationExtension.class)\npublic abstract class RestDocsTest {\n\n    protected MockMvc mockMvc;\n\n    private RestDocumentationContextProvider restDocumentation;\n\n    @BeforeEach\n    public void setUp(RestDocumentationContextProvider restDocumentation) {\n        this.restDocumentation = restDocumentation;\n    }\n\n    protected MockMvc mockController(Object controller) {\n        return MockMvcBuilders.standaloneSetup(controller)\n            .apply(MockMvcRestDocumentation.documentationConfiguration(restDocumentation))\n            .build();\n    }\n\n}\n", "id": "lc_f235eab1-d807-4118-8df3-1aae35c01226"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "7137c910-2534-4cd6-9f25-00ee1f0998d1", "tool_call_id": "call_6d12e1a78d5e4d10a4711cf6", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-08T23:50:49.356965+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Now I have a complete picture of how testing is organized in this template. Here's the explanation:\n\n---\n\n## How Testing Is Organized\n\n### JUnit 5 Tags as the Core Mechanism\n\nThe template uses **JUnit 5 `@Tag` annotations** to categorize all tests into four logical groups:\n\n| Tag | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| *(no tag)* | Standard unit tests — fast, no dependencies |\n| `context` | Spring context integration tests |\n| `restdocs` | Tests that generate Spring REST Docs (AsciiDoc) |\n| `develop` | Work-in-progress tests excluded from CI |\n\nThese tags are applied at the test-class level (e.g., `@Tag(\"restdocs\")` on the `RestDocsTest` base class in `tests/api-docs`).\n\n---\n\n### Named Test Tasks (Gradle Test Suites)\n\nThe root `build.gradle` defines **five distinct test execution paths** per subproject:\n\n#### 1. `test` (the default task — **what CI runs**)\n- Excludes tags: **`develop`** and **`restdocs`**\n- This means CI gets **unit tests + context tests**, but skips REST-docs generation and work-in-progress tests.\n\n#### 2. `unitTest`\n- Group: `verification`\n- Excludes tags: **`develop`**, **`context`**, **`restdocs`**\n- The purest subset — only fast, isolated, dependency-free tests.\n\n#### 3. `contextTest`\n- Group: `verification`\n- Includes only tag: **`context`**\n- Integration tests that boot a Spring context.\n\n#### 4. `restDocsTest`\n- Group: `verification`\n- Includes only tag: **`restdocs`**\n- Tests that exercise controllers via `MockMvc` and produce AsciiDoc snippets for API documentation. The `asciidoctor` task depends on `restDocsTest`, so docs can't be generated without these passing first.\n\n#### 5. `developTest`\n- Group: `verification`\n- Includes only tag: **`develop`**\n- Explicitly excluded from CI. The README describes this as a safe place for tests you're still writing or not confident about — \"a good tag to use if you're not good at writing tests.\"\n\n---\n\n### CI vs. Develop-Only: The Key Difference\n\n**CI** (`.github/workflows/ci.yml`) runs two steps:\n1. `checkFormat` — linting via Spring Java Format\n2. `test` — the default Gradle `test` task\n\nSince the default `test` task **excludes `develop` and `restdocs`**, CI only executes:\n- ✅ Untagged unit tests\n- ✅ `context`-tagged integration tests\n- ❌ `restdocs`-tagged API documentation tests (these run only when you explicitly invoke `restDocsTest` or build docs)\n- ❌ `develop`-tagged work-in-progress tests (these never run in CI; you invoke `developTest` locally when you want them)\n\n**Developers locally** can run any subset:\n- `./gradlew unitTest` — fast feedback\n- `./gradlew contextTest` — integration checks\n- `./gradlew restDocsTest` — regenerate API docs\n- `./gradlew developTest` — run WIP tests\n- `./gradlew test` — same as CI (unit + context, minus restdocs/develop)\n\nThis design lets developers iterate freely with `@Tag(\"develop\")` tests without breaking CI, while keeping the CI pipeline fast by also excluding the heavier `restdocs` tests.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 1190, "prompt_tokens": 12541, "total_tokens": 13731, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 421, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cached_tokens": 12160, "cache_write_tokens": 0, "video_tokens": 0}, "cost": 0, "is_byok": true, "cost_details": {"upstream_inference_cost": 0.001244811, "upstream_inference_prompt_cost": 0.000209511, "upstream_inference_completions_cost": 0.0010353}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-20260422", "system_fingerprint": null, "id": "gen-1780962624-ZYfQxwQvFlmVX76vvL2u", "finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ea9a5-041f-7e40-bdb6-